1 "§ 90-326.7. Advisory committees.
2 The Commission may appoint advisory committees to monitor all operations related to the
3 purposes of the compact and make recommendations to the Commission; provided that the
4 manner of selection and term of any committee member shall be as set forth in the Commission's
5 bylaws and rules. The Commission shall consult with an advisory committee, to the extent
6 required by the Commission's bylaws or rules, before doing any of the following:
7 (1) Approving cure criteria.
8 (2) Amending, enacting, or repealing any bylaw or rule.
9 (3) Adopting the Commission's annual budget.
10 (4) Addressing any other significant matter or taking any other significant action.
11 "§ 90-326.8. Finance.
12 (a) The Commission annually shall establish a budget to pay or provide for the payment
13 of its reasonable expenses. To fund the cost of initial operations, the Commission may accept
14 contributions and other forms of funding from the compacting states and other sources.
15 Contributions and other forms of funding from other sources shall be of such a nature that the
16 independence of the Commission concerning the performance of its duties shall not be
17 compromised.
18 (b) The Commission shall be exempt from all taxation in and by the compacting states.
19 (c) The Commission shall keep complete and accurate accounts of all of its internal
20 receipts, including grants and donations, and disbursements of all funds under its control. The
21 internal financial accounts of the Commission shall be subject to the accounting procedures
22 established under the Commission's bylaws or rules. The financial accounts and reports,
23 including the system of internal controls and procedures of the Commission, shall be audited
24 annually by an independent certified public accountant. Upon the determination of the
25 Commission but not less frequently than every three years, the review of the independent auditor
26 shall include a management and performance audit of the Commission. The Commission shall
27 make an annual report to the governors and legislatures of the compacting states, which shall
28 include a report of the independent audit. The Commission's internal accounts shall not be
29 confidential, and such materials may be shared with any compacting state upon request, provided,
30 however, that any work papers related to any internal or independent audit and any information
31 subject to the compacting states' privacy laws shall remain confidential.
32 (d) No compacting state shall have any claim or ownership of any property held by or
33 vested in the Commission or to any Commission funds held pursuant to the provisions of the
34 compact.
35 "§ 90-326.9. Records.
36 Except as to privileged records, data, and information, the laws of any compacting state
37 pertaining to confidentiality or nondisclosure shall not relieve any member of the duty to disclose
38 any relevant records, data, or information to the Commission; provided, that disclosure to the
39 Commission shall not be deemed to waive or otherwise affect any confidentiality requirement;
40 and further provided, that, except as otherwise expressly provided in the compact, the
41 Commission shall not be subject to the compacting state's laws pertaining to confidentiality and
42 nondisclosure with respect to records, data, and information in its possession. Confidential
43 information of the Commission shall remain confidential after such information is provided to
44 any member. All cure submissions received by the Commission are confidential.
45 "§ 90-326.10. Compliance.
46 The Commission shall notify a compacting state in writing of any noncompliance with
47 Commission bylaws and rules. If a compacting state fails to remedy its noncompliance within
48 the time specified in the notice, the compacting state shall be deemed to be in default as set forth
49 in G.S. 90-326.14.
50 "§ 90-326.11. Venue.
